                                                                              "message":  "- Tariffs increase the cost of imported goods, which can lead to higher prices for consumers, contributing to inflation.[](https://taxfoundation.org/research/all/federal/trump-tariffs-biden-tariffs/)\n- While tariffs can push prices up, they typically do not sustain higher inflation over years; inflation is more influenced by monetary and fiscal policies.[](https://www.forbes.com/sites/billconerly/2024/11/21/the-price-inflation-paradox-how-tariffs-really-affect-the-economy/)\n- The removal of tariffs would not significantly reduce current inflation levels due to their relatively small impact on overall price levels.[](https://www.epi.org/blog/tariff-increases-did-not-cause-inflation-and-their-removal-would-undermine-domestic-supply-chains/)\n- Trump\u0027s imposition of tariffs on Colombian goods as a retaliatory measure following the refusal of deportation flights has sparked discussions on the economic impact of such policies, including their effect on inflation and consumer goods like coffee.[](https://x.com/AOC/status/1883617048011669887)",
